<div id="aueditable"><!--DO NOT MODIFY THIS LINE AND ABOVE-->

<h1>Informal Logic</h1><div id="pubinfo"><em>First published Mon Nov 25, 1996; substantive revision Wed Jan 28, 2026</em></div>

<div id="preamble">

<p>
Informal logic (&ldquo;IL&rdquo;) is the study of reasoning and
inference as they occur in public discussion and debate, educational
and intellectual pursuits, interpersonal exchanges, and law, medicine
and other &ldquo;real-life&rdquo; contexts. IL understands the aim of
argument to be the &ldquo;epistemic betterment&rdquo; that accompanies
belief, understanding, and claims to knowledge that are made more
credible by argument. Different informal logics support this aim by
providing varying (sometimes competing) accounts of argument,
evidence, proof, and justification. The development of these accounts
is grounded in an instrumental outlook that emphasizes their
usefulness in the evaluation of everyday arguments.</p>

<p>
Blair 2015 identifies two key methodological tasks for informal logic:
(i) the development of ways to identify (and &ldquo;extract&rdquo;)
ordinary arguments from the real life exchanges in which they occur;
and (ii) the development of methods and tools that can be used to
assess their strength and cogency.</p>

<p>
Contributions to IL logic include many studies of specific kinds of
arguing. The overriding goal is a normative framework that can be
applied to ordinary arguments. In pursuit of this goal, IL addresses
topics which include: the nature and definition of arguing, argument,
and argumentation; criteria for argument evaluation; argumentation
schemes; fallacies; notions of validity; the ethics of arguing; the
argumentative use of definitions (Hitchcock 2021); argument
diagramming (&ldquo;mapping&rdquo;); cognitive biases; the history of
logic and argument analysis; artificial intelligence (AI); feminist
accounts of argument; the extent to which arguing as a practice is
inherently collaborative or adversarial (see Stevens and Cohen 2019,
Battersby and Bailin 2021; and Govier 2021); and the different norms
associated with arguing in different kinds of contexts.</p>

<p>
 <a href="http://windsor.scholarsportal.info/omp/index.php/wsia/catalog/book/123" target="other">Puppo 2019</a>
 provides a series of articles that discuss the roots and the nature
of informal logic, and many of the key issues it addresses.</p>
</div> 

<div id="toc">

<!--Entry Contents-->

<ul>

 <li><a href="#His">1. History</a></li>
 
